<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<entry xmlns:functx="http://www.functx.com" xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0"
    xml:id="entry_bitʼna" xml:lang="os">
    <form xml:lang="os-x-iron" type="lemma"><orth>bitʼna</orth></form>
    <form xml:lang="os-x-digor" type="dialectal"><orth>betʼina</orth></form>
    <sense><cit type="translation" xml:lang="ru">
            <q>мята</q>
        </cit><cit type="translation" xml:lang="en">
            <q>mint</q>
        </cit></sense>
    <cit type="exampleGroup">
        <cit type="example">
            <quote>kalm bītʼynajæ tarstī, æmæ jæ x˳ynḱʼy byl ærzadī</quote>
            <cit type="translation" xml:lang="ru">
                <q>змея боялась мяты, а та выросла у самого края ее норы</q>
            </cit>
            <cit type="translation" xml:lang="en">
                <q>the snake was afraid of mint, and it grew at the very edge of its hole</q>
            </cit>
            <bibl><ref target="#src_ЮОПам."/><biblScope>III 210</biblScope></bibl>
        </cit>
    </cit>
    <cit type="exampleGroup">
        <cit type="example">
            <quote>kalm bītʼynajæ tarstī, æmæ jæ x˳ynḱʼy byl ærzadī</quote>
            <cit type="translation" xml:lang="ru">
                <q>змея боялась мяты, а та выросла у самого края ее норы</q>
            </cit>
            <cit type="translation" xml:lang="en">
                <q>the snake was afraid of mint, and it grew at the very edge of its hole</q>
            </cit>
            <bibl><ref target="#src_ЮОПам."/><biblScope>III 210</biblScope></bibl>
        </cit>
    </cit>
    <etym xml:lang="ru">Из <mentioned xml:lang="ka"
            ><lang/><w>pʼitʼna</w><gloss><q>мята</q></gloss></mentioned>, с диссимилятивным
        озвончением начального согласного, как в <ref type="xr" target="#entry_ǵītrī"/> ‘огурец’ и
        др. (<bibl><ref target="#ref_Ахвледиани"/><biblScope>41 сл.</biblScope></bibl>). <mentioned
            xml:lang="ka"><lang/><w>pʼitʼna</w><note type="comment" xml:lang=""> ()</note><note
                type="comment" xml:lang=""> ()</note></mentioned> примыкает, в свою очередь, к
        средиземно-морским и европейским названиям мяты: <mentioned xml:lang="grc"
                ><lang/><w>μινϑη</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="la"
            ><lang/><w>mentha</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="ru"><lang/><w>мята</w><note
                type="comment" xml:lang=""> ()</note><note type="comment" xml:lang="">
            ()</note></mentioned>.%n<bibl><ref target="#ref_Вс._Миллер._ОЭ"/><biblScope>III
                14</biblScope></bibl>; <bibl><ref target="#ref_Вс._Миллер._Gr."
                /><biblScope>10</biblScope></bibl>.— <bibl><ref target="#ref_ОЯФ_I"/><biblScope>519
                сл.</biblScope></bibl></etym>
    <etym xml:lang="en">From <mentioned xml:lang="ka"
                ><lang/><w>pʼitʼna</w><gloss><q>mint</q></gloss></mentioned>, with the dissimilative
        voicing of the initial consonant, like in <ref type="xr" target="#entry_ǵītrī"/> ‘cucumeber’
        etc. (<bibl><ref target="#ref_Ахвледиани"/><biblScope>41 сл.</biblScope></bibl>). <mentioned
            xml:lang="ka"><lang/><w>pʼitʼna</w><note type="comment" xml:lang=""> ()</note><note
                type="comment" xml:lang=""> ()</note></mentioned> is close to Mediterranean and
        European names for mint: <mentioned xml:lang="grc"><lang/><w>μινϑη</w></mentioned>,
            <mentioned xml:lang="la"><lang/><w>mentha</w></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="ru"
                ><lang/><w>myata</w><note type="comment" xml:lang=""> ()</note><note type="comment"
                xml:lang=""> ()</note></mentioned>.%n<bibl><ref target="#ref_Вс._Миллер._ОЭ"
                /><biblScope>III 14</biblScope></bibl>; <bibl><ref target="#ref_Вс._Миллер._Gr."
                /><biblScope>10</biblScope></bibl>.— <bibl><ref target="#ref_ОЯФ_I"/><biblScope>519
                сл.</biblScope></bibl></etym>
</entry>
